comedy. This\npoor oid man must have been sorry\nFor rent A nice cottage on north h ever reached the century mark,\nside, close In. Inquire Standard Gro- The Hasher's Di lirium.\"- comedy,\neery Co. AH \"f Ix-uutiful things happen\nFor Sale A snap, one second hand h'm-\nApply\nupright Decker Bros, piano.\n120 Court St.\nFor rent House corner Alia and\nCollege streets, opposite Presbyterian\nchurch. Apply to F- E. Judd.\nFix up your\" roofs with the beat\nshipment of shingles ever received In\nPendleton. Crab Creek Lumber Co.\nAn extra new lot of ladies' oxfords,\npatent, gun metal, tans In dew short\nvamps and military heels. Choice,\nSI. 86.\n.fllixandors tJuno white sale and\ncompetitive sale will continue all next\nweek, Including Saturday evening.\n.Tune 18.\nOnly two Leonard cleanable refrig\nerators left at Sharon Eddlngs.\nYou'll have to hurry to get one of\nthese Ice savers.\nN'ext Wednesday you will sny \"I\nwish I hnd bought one of those Ap\nplet!. n orchard tracts.\" After Tues\nday nt 10 n. m., wl'l be too late\nDo you care whither you use the\nbest coal? Then see us. We Just re\nceived the best shipment of coal ob\ntainable. Crab Creek Lumber company.\n1K( I S Wil li BE IN\nTOWN NEXT\nFRIDAY\nWhen Campbell Brothers' Big Con\nsolidated Shows come to town, It Is\na sure sign that labor will he sus\npended and all take a holiday as there\nwill be sights to see all day beginning\nat 10 a. m. with the grnnd street pa\nrade nnd entering with the two big\nshows under waterproof tents nt 2\ntill 8 p. m. Will exhibit here Friday,\nJune 7.\nOLD STOCK RANGE -OUEiNUSE\nIRRIGATION DITCH MAKES\nGOOD GRAZING AGAIN\nMcCulloiigli Itrotlicrs Have 1000 Head\nof Cuttle on Itungo Out From Echo\nWhich Is 1'lrst Time in Four Years\nSuch a Tiling Huh Keen Possible.\n(Special Correspondence.)\nEcho, Ore., June 11. The Mc\nCullough Brothers have over a thou\nsand head of cattle on their summer\nrange west of here Just beyond lower\nButter creek.. This Is the first time\nin four years there has been any feed\nfor stock on this range during the\nsummer. At one time thousands of\nhead of stock grazed here until the\nfeed was completely exhausted. But\nsince the advent of the various Irri\ngation ditches a new grass and vari\nous weeds have sprung up making the\nplace once more a profitable feedlhg\nground and bringing back a remem\nbrance of the old dayB when stock\nraising was the sole industry of this\nvicinity.\nJerry Borland returned yesterday\nevening from Shaniko, where he has\nbeen absent on business the past few\ndays.\nOscar Doble returned to his home\nat Irrigon yesterday morning.\nMr. and Mrs. S. T. Roberts went up\nto Pendleton this morning to attend\nthe wedding- of Mr. Robers' sister,\nMiss Verna Rogerts.\nMrs. Jas. McLaughlin spent yester\nday In Pendleton.\nJ. L. McCullough went to Pendleton\nmi the motor this morning.\nAT THE PICTURE SHOWS MILTON ODD FELLOWS\nENJOY BID BANQUET\n(Special Correspondence.)\nMilton, Ore., June 10. One of the\nfinest banquets ever given In Milton\nwas the one given last night In the\nbanquet room of the I. O. O. F. tem\nple, by the Encampment of Odd Fel\nlows. The Froewater encampment\nwas present nnd a most enjoyable\nevening was spent. Music by the\nMilton Aeolian band, and speeches by\ndifferent members was the mode of\nentertainment.\nMrs. T. C. Frazior was accompanied\nby her brother, Mr. Powell Plants on\nher return home from an extended\nvisit In Oitford. Miss. Mr. Plants will\nspend the summer In Milton.\nMiss Grace Hewitt daughter of Tom\nHewitt, arrived in the city this week\nfrom Red Oak, Iowa, and will make\nher home with her father.\nChildren's day will be observed In\nthe M. E. church Sunday morning. An\nelaborate program has been arranged\nboth musical and literary.\nBorn, to Mr. and Mrs. Charles Tay\nlor of Sunnyside. a baby girl.\nRev. and Mrs. Leslie Obert took\ntheir departure today for Tangent.\nOre., where Mr. Obert is pastor of the\nChristian church for this summer In\nthe fall Mr. Obert will move to Eu\ngene where he will enter school to re\nsume his studies.\nMr. and Mrs. J. E. Cherry and son\nDale, were guests of friends near the\npower plant this afternoon.\ni:N Til WI'L INDICATES\nRET I'll OP PROSPERITY\nNew York. It will be interesting\ni to learn how those Iconclasts who are\nl never so happy as when they are\npreaching the doctrme of discontent\nand hard times, will Interpret the\nenormous bookings for European\nports reported by all of the steamship\nl companies for this month. Indica\ni lions point to the largest exodus\ni since the year of the panic. The\n1 '\"\"gakdemand f\"r tickets Is taken by\nI the \"flcials of the companies as a\nlire tok. n of the return of prosperity,\nI V I I N BIRD A MNGl'lST.\nA Ten Days Clearance Sale\nAt Wohlenberg Department Store\nSpecial attention is called to the great slaughter of prices in our Shoe Department, where\nnew desirable footwear is offered at a big reduction. Also remember the Special Savings in\nall kinds of READY-TO-WEAR DRESSES, SUITS, COATS, UNDERWEAR, ETC.\nThe extraordinary low prices quoted in this sale are made necessary by the coming enlarge-\nj. i t .1 i t 1 liJ T Jl.i -t iL.\nilium aim improvement oi inis store, wnicn, wuen cumpiewu, win give -renaieion one vi uie ir\nnicest, Dest apportioned stores in tne couniry. i\nThe Prices Hold Good Until June 15\nli\nSilk and Kid Gloves 5)\nSensational Reductions\non Combination Suits\nDuring this Clearance Sale.\nAll $1.35 Combinations now\nAll $1.50 Combinations now\nAll $1.75 Combinations now\nAll 2.00 Combinations now\nAll $2.25 Combinations now\nAll $2.50 Combinations now\nAll $3.00 Combinations now\nAll $3.50 Combinations now\nAll $4.00 Combinations now\nAll $5.00 Combinations now\nAll $0.00 Combinations now\nAll $7.50 Combinations now\nAll $10.00 Combinations now\n98\n91.15\n?1.35\n?1.65\n?1.85\n?2.15\n?2.35\n$2.85\n?3.25\n?3.95\n$4.95\n6.35\n?7.95\nat these prices\n65c Silk Gloves, all colors, at\n$1.00 Silk Gloves, all 