ntiseptic nature it gets the germs\nnlao. Encli bottle is equipped with n shnkcr cork which\nnuikes it quite easy to apply.\nThe Drug Store That Serve You Best.\nItn--Volonl I'iimI Slunk \"Throe Lan\nguages. New York. There Is a guest nt the\nW'oleott who Is literally a bird, a my\nnn bird. His name Is Timothy and\nhe came originally from Nepal, a\nmountainous district of northeast In\ndia. Timothy is owned by Mrs. H. T.\nChilds of Rochester. Timothy was\nfound In Singapore three years ago\nin a little bazar kept by a Chinaman.\nHe had not many feathers then, but\nMrs. Childs. who was making a trip\naround the world, heard him speak\nand promptly boueht him. Since then\nhe has treveled with her wherever\nshe lias gone. He is about a foot\nlong, with a slender body, the upper\npart of which is purple. The tail Is\niridisceiit with purple, preen nnd most\nof the colors of the rainbow.\nHe has a long, pointed beak, the\ntop of his head looks like velvet nnd\nat the hack of his neck are two bright\nm IIow wattles that irivo the effect of\na eollar.\nTimothy's vocabulary has n won\nderful ranee, covering parts of three'\nlanguages, Knglish, French and Japa\nnese. His voice is not at nil like that\nof the common parrot, for he usually\naffects n deep bass.\nmoiM'trs OF AYOOLKX\nMILLS ON DISPLAY\nAn unusually handsome exhibit of\ntlie products of the rendleton woolen\nmills is on display In a sixth street\nwindow of Meier Frank's says tho\nPortland Journal. Among the pro\nduets of the mill shown Is an elegant\nbath robe, which was fabricated to\norder for James J. Jeffries.\nMajor Lee Moorhouse who Is In\ncharge of the exhibit has arranged a\ntypical t'mntMla Indian tepee, a brave\narrayed in n gorgeous Indian blanket\nnnd numerous Indian relies, ns a set\nting for the display, which Includes\nbath robes. Indian robes, fine white\nMankots and steamer rugs.\nThe rendleton Woolen Mills has In\ntroduced its product all over the Unit\ned States nnd has become famous for\nthe manufacture of Indian robes. The\nmill is a valuable advertiser of one\nof Oregon's principal products, ns It\nuses nothlngln the manufacture of\nits blankets nnd robes but pure Ore\ngon fleece wool.\nNEWS THAT BREWS\nIN ATHENA'S MIDST\n(Special Correspondence.)\nAthena, Ore., June 11. The funer\nal of the aged pioneer. Grandmother\nGerklng was held from the Christian\nchurch onFriday afternoon and was\nvery largely attended.\nThe auto microbe has entered the\nveins of Dr. Newsom and he has plac\ned an order for an \"Overland,\" one\nof the latest up-to-date machines.\nMiss Cecile Boyd, daughter of ye\nKditor Boyd is at home on a vacation\nfrom the normal at Lewiston, Idaho.\nMiss Alta Sharp went to Spokane\nto meet her sister returning from\nMontana this week.\nMat. Mosgrove of Milton was a vis\nitor in town Thursday.\nA meeting of the voters of school\ndistrict No. 29, Athena, is called for\nMonday, July 20. to elect one director\nand a clerk.\nLeft, on Wednesday morning's\ntrain, via Portland, for Vale, Malheur\nCo., where she resides, Mrs. N. E.\nTaggart, mother of T. M. Taggart of\nthis city.\nMiss Delia Darr of Adams was a\nvisitor at her sister's, Mrs. Harry Mc\nT.ride this week.\nThe Athena department store has\nbeen sold to Mr. Jesse G. Campbell of\nSpokane, who Is now In charge. The\nretiring owner, Mr. Brown, will re\nside In Spokane.\nCasper Woodward. a prosperous\nanchor came in Friday to give his\nauto some repair attention.\nThe continued dry weather is giv\ning the gardners nnd wheat growers\nsome little anxiety.\nMrs. Chas. Downing has returned\nfrom the hospital at Walla Waila very\nmuch improved.\nII. M. Sloan of the Pendleton Iron\nworks, was in town Friday attending\n1'ie funeral of Mrs. Gerking, a rela\ntive. W. A. Gibson of Pendleton, was in\nAthena Friday.\nLawyer Watts visited the county\ncapitol on Thursday.\nSam Small the noted evangelist will\nbe ill Athena on Thursday 16. and\nspeak at the-M. V.\nnlng.\nMr. DeHoff of Seattle, was a vis\nitor in this city on Friday.\nJ. R. Brown of Pendleton, came up\nfrom that city Friday.\nCALL FOR. WARRANTS.\nAll general fund warrants regis\ntered during the months of January.\nFebruary and March, 1910, will be\npaid at my office In the county court\nhouse upon presentation.\nInterest ceased upon date of publi\ncation. Dated Pendleton, Oregon, June 11,\n1910. G. W. BRADLEY,\nTreasurer Umatilla County.\nNotice.\nThe Oregon Journal has appointed\nM. Alfred Fitz Gerald their agent for\nPendleton, who will take charge of all\ndeliveries and make all collections for\nthe paper. Any Inattention on the\npart of the carrier or otherwise, will\nbe promptly attended to if reported to\nagent at 619 Johnson St., or telephone\nBlack 7871.\nModern Wooumen Meeting.\nAttention Modern Woodmen of Am\nerica. Regular meeting tonight; initi\nation. J. D. FINNEY, Clerk.\nFort St,. James\nOn Lake Stuart,\nBRITISH COLUMBIA\nThis is destined to be the Portland\nof British Columbia, on a navigable\nriver and deep water lake with two\ntrains running in next fall.\nLetters pour into our office all day\nwith applications for lots. To those\nwho cannot come in we would do our\nutmost to make a good selection.\nPrice $100 and $200 each. Cash\n$25.00. balance $10.00 a month. A\nfew 40 acre farms Joining Fort St.\nJames townsite and Lake Stuart,\n$50.00 cash and $10.00 a month,\niiu need not be n Canadian Citien\nto Hold This.\nYou need not improve it. nor you\nneed not reside on it. All this land\nis on or near the railroad. Grand\nTrunk Pacific. Alaska Yukon, and\nCanadian Northern railroads.\nRich farm lands, JS.Rn per acre,\nft tOvJ\n\"-JuyV\nrV--.... Occob\noprri(bi i( by OutctuJt AdrcrtUtnf C., Cbf\nJune 11, 1910.\nRear Friend:\nThe Sunday schools of Umatilla\ncounty will hold a picnic in the\npark at this place on Thursday 16.\n$3.00 cash, and balance $1.00 per acre\nchurch in the eve- per year until paid.\n'APPLY CANADIAN NOKTUKHN\nLAND COMPANY,\n301. 305 and 306 Lewis Building.\nPortland, Oregon.\nJuly 4 th will soon be here. Won't\nyou be glad? We will have a plc-nlc\nthen. Mama told me this morning\nto go down to Clark's grocery and get\na whole lot of things for the 4th.\nThey keep everything In the Pre\nferred Stock and Closset Deverea\nlines.\nYour friend,\nJACOB.\nP. S. We like the Schram automat\nic fruit jars much the best. Mr.\nClark keeps them. We don't trade\nanywhere but at\nCLARK'S\nGROCERY\nFb.cme Main 174.\n5t4-\"i46 Main Street.\nThe persistence of faith, despite the\nlack of outward proof, is a divine dem\nonstration of Something that throws\non the human mind a reflection which\nlike an image on a screen, cannot be\naccounted for unless it be Itself the\nsubstance of things hoped for and\nevidence of things not seen. Until we\nreach the reality, let us rest In the\nsign. Bnrtol.\nSPECIAL! SPECIAL! SPECIAL!\nPEACOCK NOVELTY GLASSWARE\nAll Colors, All Designs. The prettiest, and the greate t Special Price offer\nwe have ever attempetd\nBon Bon Dishes\nFruit Saucers\nOlive Dishes\nPickle Dishes\nJelly Dishes\nFooted Jelly Dishes\nYour Choice 15c\nFRUIT BOWLS\nBERRY BOWLS\nFLOWER VASES\nEach 25c\nSee Window Display Electric Vacuum Carpet Cleaner for Rent..\nINGRAM'S GROCERY m\" SiJtfiLSr EvM\nI","height":"27508","width":"19280"}}
